      <paragraph>
        <num><b>1.</b></num>
        <content>
          <p><b>Summary of proposal </b></p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>​​​A foundation year (sometimes referred to as Year 0) is a one-year programme of study, typically offered by universities, to enable students without the necessary prior attainment, specific knowledge, or qualifications in the appropriate subject/s to progress onto the first year of their chosen undergraduate course. </p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>From academic year 2025/26, maximum tuition fee and loan limits for classroom-based foundation years in subjects assigned to Price Group D by the Office for Students (OfS)<authorialNote marker="1"><p> The Office for Students assigns subjects to one of six price group (A, B, C1.1, C1.2, C2 and D) for funding purposes based on their characteristics and associated teaching costs. For more information see <a href="https://www.officeforstudents.org.uk/media/2ptb3ono/guide-to-funding-2024-25.pdf"><u>https://www.officeforstudents.org.uk/media/2ptb3ono/guide-to-funding-2024-25.pdf</u></a> </p></authorialNote> will be lowered to £5,760. The maximum tuition fee and loan limits for all other foundation year subjects will remain aligned with the maximum fee limit for standard full-time undergraduate courses (which is due to increase to £9,535 in academic year 2025/26). </p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num><b>2.</b></num>
        <content>
          <p><b>Strategic case for proposed regulation </b></p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Foundation years are recognised as a valuable pathway into higher education (HE) for adult learners, including those from under-represented or disadvantaged backgrounds. More generally, foundation years offer a second chance for students who have not achieved their potential.</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>The number of UK students on foundation years has increased rapidly in recent years, rising from 7,960 in 2011/12 to 71,980 in 2022/23, equating to an average per annum increase of more than 20%.<authorialNote marker="2"><p> Internal analysis of HESA data. </p></authorialNote> The number of HE providers in England offering foundation year provision has increased from 52 to 106 over the same period, with medium, low and unknown tariff providers accounting for 70% of all foundation year providers in 2022/23.<authorialNote marker="3"><p> Ibid.</p></authorialNote></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>The Independent Panel (chaired by Sir Philip Augar) to the Review of Post-18 Education and Funding expressed concern about the rapid and disproportionate growth in foundation years<authorialNote marker="4"><p> <a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/5ceeb35740f0b62373577770/Review_of_post_18_education_and_funding.pdf"><u>https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/5ceeb35740f0b62373577770/Review_of_post_18_education_and_funding.pdf</u></a> </p></authorialNote> notably within subject groups which do not carry the expectation of special entry requirements (e.g. business and administrative studies) and within low to medium entry tariff providers (which possess a high proportion of students from low-income households) and questioned whether the significant expansion of foundation years had always been in the best interests of students and taxpayers.<authorialNote marker="5"><p> Ibid.</p></authorialNote></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>The core issue is that foundation years are a more expensive route into higher education when compared to functionally similar alternatives such as Access to HE (AHE) Diplomas which seek to achieve broadly the same outcomes as foundation years (i.e. to prepare students for HE study) and are delivered in further education settings. </p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>While learners on AHE Diplomas typically pay lower fees and can apply for an Advanced Learner Loan (ALL) to help cover course costs, foundation year students currently pay up to £9,250 in tuition fees, the same as for subsequent years of undergraduate degree study, which they may choose to fund by taking out a government-backed tuition fee loan from the Student Loans Company (SLC). These loans are subsidised by taxpayers. This means that students choosing the foundation year route are more likely to be taking on additional levels of debt compared to those choosing less costly further education alternatives. </p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>For some subjects, such as business and social sciences, which do not typically have subject-specific entry or skills requirements, the additional year of study is not always necessary. The growth of foundation years entrants has been mainly concentrated in Price Group D (classroom-based subjects), as shown in Figure 1. Data shows that growth in the take-up of foundation years has been fastest in Business and Management studies where the number of entrants grew by 25% between 2015/16 and 2018/19 and by 160% between 2019/20 and 2022/23.<authorialNote marker="6"><p> Internal analysis of HESA data. Separate growth rates reflect subject classification system change in 2019/20 (see footnote 12). </p></authorialNote> In 2022/23, 49% of all UK foundation year entrants were enrolled on Business and Management subjects (compared to 20% of first-year undergraduate entrants).<authorialNote marker="7"><p> Internal analysis of HESA data.</p></authorialNote> Table 2 overleaf provides a summary of change in foundation years students and first year undergraduates from 2015/16 to 2022/23, across several subjects.</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Figure 1: Number of foundation year students, by provider typology and OfS Price </b><b>Group of subjects studied (2022/23)</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><i>Internal analysis of HESA data.</i></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>It should be noted that 28% of HE providers who delivered (first) undergraduate degrees with an integrated foundation year in 2022/23 (106 of 343 approved fee cap HE providers) provided all or part of this provision via franchise partners (see Table 1 below).</p>
