        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Why is government action necessary?</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Effective price-cap regulation is needed to ensure that HE and the underlying funding and student finance system remains fair, affordable and delivers good value for money for students and taxpayers. Tuition fees and loans for UK domiciled students on foundation years at HE providers in England are subject to price-cap regulation in the same way as UK domiciled students on standard undergraduate courses. The maximum fee and loan limit for undergraduate courses (which includes foundation years), is currently set at £9,250 for the 2024/25 academic year for full-time courses. This is due to increase to £9,535 in 2025/26.<authorialNote marker="8"><p> More information on the tuition fee and loan system in England can be found within a separate IA on tuition fee increase for academic year 2025/26.</p></authorialNote></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Students do not always have access to complete or high-quality information about their post-18 study options, making it difficult for them to assess the quality and value for money for different courses and pathways to HE. As such, they are at risk of making poorly informed decisions about their learning which do not suit their needs, ability, and financial position or do not represent good value for money.<authorialNote marker="9"><p> <a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/693188/Influence_of_finance_on_higher_education_decision-making.pdf"><u>https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/693188/Influence_of_finance_on_higher_education_decision-making.pdf</u></a></p></authorialNote></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>The current disparity in costs means students choosing the more expensive foundation year route can end up taking out higher levels of debt overall compared to their peers. This is particularly unfair since these students are more likely to be from under-represented and disadvantaged backgrounds. These are groups which tend to face comparatively greater financial barriers to participation in HE.<authorialNote marker="10"><p> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-student-finance-system-impact-on-disadvantaged-young-people"><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-student-finance-system-impact-on-disadvantaged-young-people</u></a> </p></authorialNote></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <content>
          <p>Without action, foundation years in classroom-based subjects would continue to represent poor value for money for students with provision continuing to expand in a way which does not best serve the interests of students and taxpayers.</p>
