      <paragraph>
        <num><b>3.</b></num>
        <content>
          <p><b>SMART objectives for intervention</b></p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Under the preferred option, maximum tuition fee and loan limits for foundation years in classroom-based subjects (currently designated as Price Group D by the OfS) would be lowered to £5,760. The maximum tuition fee and loan limits for all other foundation year subjects would remain aligned with the maximum fee limit for standard full-time undergraduate courses (which is due to increase to £9,535 in academic year 2025/26). </p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>The lower tuition fee limits will apply to HE providers registered with the OfS in England, while the lower fee loan limits will apply to English-domiciled students wishing to study classroom-based foundation years anywhere in the UK. The change to loan limits will mean that English students wishing to study classroom-based foundation years in the devolved administrations (DAs) will have their fee loans reduced.</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>By lowering the maximum tuition fee HE providers can charge for classroom-based foundation years, we expect to see provision expanding at a much slower rate. Research commissioned by the DfE to inform this policy found that the costs of foundation years can vary, reflecting in part differences in quality, with some provision in classroom-based subjects being delivered for significantly less than the current fee limit for the 2024/25 academic year (£9,250).<authorialNote marker="14"><p> <a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/1170788/Understanding_the_costs_of_foundation_years_study_research_report.pdf"><u>https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/1170788/Understanding_the_costs_of_foundation_years_study_research_report.pdf</u></a> </p></authorialNote> Therefore, by lowering tuition fees for classroom-based subjects to a level potentially below the cost of delivering them, HE providers will be encouraged to deliver this provision more efficiently or consider whether more students can be offered direct entry to undergraduate courses (without a foundation year) having studied A-Levels or functionally similar provision (such as AHE Diplomas).</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>The scale of the potential reduction in provision of classroom-based foundation years as a result of lower tuition fees and loan limits will depend on the behavioural response of HE providers and students to the lowering of fees which is difficult to predict accurately.</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>On the supply side, HE providers would likely scale back or withdraw some provision in classroom-based subjects because it is not financially viable at the lower fee level (since the lower tuition fee is not sufficient to cover the cost of teaching). However, it is also possible that some HE providers may choose to continue offering these foundation years at current levels, for example by cross subsidising the losses on this provision with surpluses generated by other activities or by finding ways to reduce delivery costs. </p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>On the demand side, the response of students is more ambiguous. Lowering tuition fees for classroom-based foundation years may encourage more students to enrol on this provision as they perceive the cost of study and the level of debt they would need to take out, to be lower. Conversely, some students may be discouraged from taking up classroom-based foundation years if they perceive lower fees to be a signal of lower quality or poorer outcomes. We think the behavioural response of students to any change in fee levels is likely to be minimal. This is because HE students are assumed to be price insensitive with available evidence showing that prospective students consider a range of price and non-price factors when making decisions about whether to go to university and evidence shows that tuition fees/course costs are not the most influential factor.<authorialNote marker="15"><p> <a href="https://www.rand.org/pubs/research_reports/RR571.html"><u>https://www.rand.org/pubs/research_reports/RR571.html</u></a></p></authorialNote>,<authorialNote marker="16"><p> <a href="http://ftp.iza.org/dp8364.pdf"><u>http://ftp.iza.org/dp8364.pdf</u></a> </p></authorialNote>,<authorialNote marker="17"><p> <a href="https://ifs.org.uk/sites/default/files/output_url_files/wp1117.pdf"><u>https://ifs.org.uk/sites/default/files/output_url_files/wp1117.pdf</u></a> </p></authorialNote></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Overall, we do not expect this policy to significantly reduce the number of people entering HE. This is because we expect prospective students who would otherwise have chosen a classroom-based foundation year to either choose to undertake functionally similar courses (such as AHE Diplomas) or enter directly into year 1 where they are able to do so. Either choice will lead to lower levels of student loan debt and reduced costs for taxpayers.</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>The intended effects and outcomes of lowering tuition fees and loan limits can be considered specific, measurable, achievable, realistic and time-limited (SMART). The policy objective is specifically targeted at stemming the rapid expansion in classroom-based foundation years. The impact of the policy will be possible to measure by reviewing data on the number of students enrolling onto classroom-based foundation years after the policy has been implemented. A reduction in these numbers, plateauing, or a contraction in the rate of growth compared to previous years, would indicate that the policy has had its intended impact. Delivery discussions with the Student Loans Company (SLC) have confirmed that the policy is deliverable, and engagement with HE providers has indicated that many will scale back their provision of classroom-based foundation years, meaning that the objectives of the policy are<i> </i>realistic. We expect the policy to have an immediate and lasting impact, due to a sustained reduction in funding for classroom-based foundation years.</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>A key measure of success will be change to the rapid growth in the supply of classroom-based foundation years offered by HE providers, on the assumption that the lower tuition fee will reduce the financial incentive for HE providers to continue delivering foundation years in classroom-based subjects at current levels. In academic year 2025/26, our minimal expectation is to see growth in student enrolments onto classroom-based foundation years reflect the overall growth rate for year 1 entry. Growth has already slowed down in academic year 2022/23, with a growth of only 4% from academic year 2021/22. </p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>We would also expect to see a reduction in the cost to students, either as result of students choosing foundation years at the lower fee rate, or because students choose alternative routes for access to HE (e.g. via AHE Diplomas or direct entry into year 1). Additionally, monetary savings from this policy will extend to government and taxpayers due to a reduction in the amount of student loan outlay for classroom-based foundation years.</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num><b>4.</b></num>
        <content>
          <p><b>Description of proposed intervention options and explanation of the</b><b> logical change process whereby this achieves SMART objectives</b></p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>In February 2022, the Department for Education published a consultation on HE reforms.<authorialNote marker="18"><p> <a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/64b158dc9959000013002b06/Higher_education_policy_statement_and_reform_-_government_consultation_response_-_equality_analysis.pdf"><u>https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/64b158dc9959000013002b06/Higher_education_policy_statement_and_reform_-_government_consultation_response_-_equality_analysis.pdf</u></a> </p></authorialNote> This included proposals for lowering tuition fee and loan limits for foundation years in all subjects to a level that ensured they remained an accessible and attractive route into HE, while also becoming more fairly priced and more affordable for students and taxpayers.</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>The consultation received 298 responses to the written questions, including from HE providers, HE mission groups, HE sector representative bodies, arm’s length and professional bodies, student representative bodies, and individuals. Views gathered on foundation years showed a slight preference of opinion against the department’s proposal: 43% of respondents agreed that foundation year fee limits should be reduced, while 57% disagreed. The majority of HE providers that responded disagreed that foundation year fee limits should be reduced, whereas a majority of individuals, student mission groups, and further education providers that responded agreed with the proposed reduction.<b> </b>Of the 183 respondents who commented on whether there was a case for allowing foundation years in some subjects to charge a higher tuition fee, just under two thirds disagreed with this proposal, with HE providers more likely to disagree compared to other respondents.<authorialNote marker="19"><p> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/higher-education-reform-consultation-analysis-research-report"><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/higher-education-reform-consultation-analysis-research-report</u></a> </p></authorialNote></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>In its consultation response, published in July 2023,<authorialNote marker="20"><p> <a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/64b158dc9959000013002b06/Higher_education_policy_statement_and_reform_-_government_consultation_response_-_equality_analysis.pdf"><u>https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/64b158dc9959000013002b06/Higher_education_policy_statement_and_reform_-_government_consultation_response_-_equality_analysis.pdf</u></a> </p></authorialNote> the department announced that it would target the tuition fee reduction at foundation years in classroom-based subjects (defined as OfS Price Group D), where growth in student enrolments has been most concentrated, and where evidence indicated teaching costs were the lowest. This proposal was deemed to represent a fair compromise between maintaining the viability of higher cost foundation year provision — so that it can continue to widen access to HE — and ensuring that students can access lower cost foundation years provision at a fairer fee, where provision can be delivered more efficiently. </p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Summary and preferred option and description of implementation plan</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>As part of the policy development process a range of different options were considered. These are discussed in section 5 below.</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Under the preferred option (Option 1), the maximum fee and loan limit for foundation years in classroom-based subjects (currently in OfS Price Group D) will be lowered to £5,760 while the maximum fee and loan limit for foundation years in all other subjects will remain aligned with the maximum fee limit for standard full-time undergraduate courses (due to increase to £9,535 for the 2025/26 academic year). The new lower fee limit will apply from the start of the 2025/26 academic year. </p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>The £5,760 lower fee limit was chosen to align with the highest standard funding rate for AHE Diplomas, which are functionally similar to foundation years. AHE Diplomas are priced at five different rates and can be funded via grant funding or Advanced Learner Loans. The department considered aligning the lower fee limit with the lowest base funding rate for AHE Diplomas, which would have produced a lower fee limit of £3,600. It also considered aligning the lower fee with the highest specialist funding rate, which would have produced a lower fee limit of £7,200. £3,600 was considered to be too low and could have had an overly detrimental impact on the provision of foundation years and on HE sector finances. Research into the cost of foundation years provision also found no evidence that they could be delivered for this amount.<authorialNote marker="21"><p> <a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/1170788/Understanding_the_costs_of_foundation_years_study_research_report.pdf"><u>https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/1170788/Understanding_the_costs_of_foundation_years_study_research_report.pdf</u></a> </p></authorialNote> The £7,200 limit was deemed too high, representing an insufficient reduction in funding, unlikely to stem the disproportionate growth of foundation years in classroom-based subjects. The specialist AHE rate also applies to a small number of subjects (e.g. agriculture and music) which do not sit within the scope of classroom-based subjects, which the £5,760 fee limit will apply to.</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>The setting of lower fee levels for classroom-based foundation years will be delivered through secondary legislation. An affirmative statutory instrument will be laid in Parliament to amend the Higher Education (Fee Limits and Fee Limits Condition) (England) Regulations 2018, and a negative instrument will be laid in Parliament to amend the Education (Student Support) Regulations 2011. </p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>The reduced tuition fee loans for classroom-based foundation years will be administered to students by the SLC, who have responsibility for ensuring that correct levels of student loan funding are only offered to eligible students studying eligible courses (including foundation years).</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Since the policy was originally announced on 17 July 2023, HE providers have had some time to plan and prepare for these changes, including experimenting, piloting and/or trialling different ways of delivering foundation year provision with the reduced fee limit. The department also published guidance on 9 May 2024 to help HE providers prepare for these changes.<authorialNote marker="22"><p> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/higher-education-tuition-fees-for-foundation-years"><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/higher-education-tuition-fees-for-foundation-years</u></a></p></authorialNote> The regulations do not seek to place any undue constraints on the ability of HE providers to develop, test and roll-out different forms of foundation year provision. They simply seek to impose new lower fee limits for some foundation years which can be implemented within existing course design and registration processes.</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Figure 2 below presents the logic model for the preferred option.</p>
