      <paragraph>
        <num><b>5.</b></num>
        <content>
          <p><b>Summary of long-list and alternatives</b></p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>In May 2019, the Independent Panel (chaired by Sir Philip Augar) that supported the Review of Post-18 Education and Funding recommended withdrawing financial support for all foundation years attached to degree courses, with exemptions for specific courses such as medicine.<authorialNote marker="23"><p> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/post-18-review-of-education-and-funding-independent-panel-report"><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/post-18-review-of-education-and-funding-independent-panel-report</u></a> </p></authorialNote> The previous government rejected this option, concluding that absolute removal of foundation years’ funding would have a detrimental impact on access to HE – particularly for students from underrepresented backgrounds. </p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Within the consultation on HE reform,<authorialNote marker="24"><p> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/higher-education-policy-statement-and-reform"><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/higher-education-policy-statement-and-reform</u></a>   </p></authorialNote> the department consulted on whether there was a case for lowering all foundation year fees to align with AHE Diplomas, with some exceptions, but respondents felt that lowering tuition fees in this way would make foundation years financially unviable to deliver. This option was also rejected, and the department commissioned further research from IFF Research into the delivery costs of foundation years.<authorialNote marker="25"><p> <a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/64b16c60995900000d002b25/Understanding_the_costs_of_foundation_years_study_research_report.pdf"><u>https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/64b16c60995900000d002b25/Understanding_the_costs_of_foundation_years_study_research_report.pdf</u></a> </p></authorialNote> This research found some evidence to suggest that a proportion of classroom-based subjects were being delivered for less than the current maximum fee limit of £9,250. As a result, a more targeted option was developed (see below).  </p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>This policy was announced alongside a wider package of measures for HE reform.<authorialNote marker="26"><p> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/higher-education-policy-statement-and-reform"><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/higher-education-policy-statement-and-reform</u></a>   </p></authorialNote> The department considered whether extending some of the other reforms in this announcement (i.e. Recruitment Limits and Minimum Eligibility Requirements) to foundation years could have addressed the problems identified in previous sections. Recruitment limits for foundation years was discounted on the basis that the OfS’ B3 metrics – used to apply recruitment limits – already cover courses with foundation years, and a more punitive system of recruitment limits disregards the important role of foundation years in widening access and participation to HE. Minimum Eligibility Requirements for foundation years were also discounted on similar grounds. To widen access to HE, it is often necessary for foundation years to be available with lower entry requirements, and providers must retain the ability to consider non-traditional entry qualifications when offering foundation year places.  </p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <heading>As part of the policy development process a range of different options were considered on the best approach for lowering tuition fee and loan limits for classroom-based foundation year subjects in a way which would achieve the desired policy objectives. The full list of options, which are all covered in this impact assessment, are set out below:</heading>
        <paragraph>
          <num><b>•</b></num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Option 0 - Do nothing. </b>This option would leave maximum foundation year tuition fees and loan limits unchanged. Providers would continue to be able to charge fees up to the maximum fee limit for the relevant academic year (currently £9,250 for 2024/25, due to increase to £9,535 for the 2025/26 academic year) across all subjects.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num><b>•</b></num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Option 1 (</b><b>preferred approach)</b><b> - Lowering maximum tuition fee and loan limits to £5,760 for foundation years in classroom-based subjects </b>(currently in OfS Price Group D) with maximum tuition fee and loan limits for foundation years in all other subjects remaining aligned with the maximum fee limit for standard undergraduate courses (currently £9,250 for 2024/25, and due to increase to £9,535 for academic year 2025/26).</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>•</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Option 2 - Lowering the maximum tuition fee cap to £5,760 for foundation years across all subjects</b>.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num><b>•</b></num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Option 3 - Lowering the maximum tuition fee limit to £5,760 across all foundation years provision and topping up providers’ grant funding by £2k for each enrolment on higher cost and strategically important subjects.</b></p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>•</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Option 4 - Non-regulatory option </b>(e.g. developing improved advice and guidance for prospective students).</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Option 2 was rejected due to concern that this could negatively impact the ability of students from underrepresented groups to access HE, particularly in higher-cost subjects that are important to the future skills needs of the UK economy. This was on the basis that lowering foundation year tuition fees across all subjects would make those subjects which are more expensive to teach (e.g. medicine, dentistry and STEM) financially unviable to the point that HE providers could withdraw them.<authorialNote marker="27"><p> <a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/64b16c60995900000d002b25/Understanding_the_costs_of_foundation_years_study_research_report.pdf"><u>https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/64b16c60995900000d002b25/Understanding_the_costs_of_foundation_years_study_research_report.pdf</u></a> </p></authorialNote></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Option 3 was rejected on affordability grounds in that it would be costly for the taxpayer compared to other options since it would require higher levels of direct grant funding to cover the shortfall in funding for courses in higher cost and strategically important subjects (such as medicine, dentistry and STEM).</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Option 4 was rejected because it was deemed highly unlikely that HE providers would take the necessary action themselves to reduce tuition fees for foundation years so that they are more aligned with alternative, further education options such as AHE Diplomas. This is because HE providers have a clear incentive to set higher tuition fees for their courses; firstly, to cover the rising cost of teaching, and secondly, to signal that their courses are of high quality. A non-regulatory option based on providing better information to students on foundation years and AHE Diplomas was also rejected because it was deemed unlikely to be effective. Even with better information for students, HE providers would be unlikely to reduce tuition fees voluntarily, meaning that students who continue to study classroom-based foundation years would still be paying higher fees. </p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num><b>6.</b></num>
        <content>
          <p><b>Description of shortlisted policy options carried forward </b></p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <heading>The options under consideration are: </heading>
        <paragraph>
          <num>•</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Option 0 (Do nothing) – </b>This option would leave foundation year tuition fees and loans unchanged. Providers would continue to be able to charge fees up to the maximum fee limit across all subjects (£9,535 from academic year 2025/26) </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>•</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Option 1 (Preferred approach) – </b>Differential fees with a maximum fee limit of £5,760 for classroom-based subjects (currently in OfS Price Group D) and a maximum fee for all other subjects remaining aligned with the maximum fee limit for standard undergraduate courses (£9,535 for academic year 2025/26).</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </level>
      <level>
        <heading>The critical success factors this policy seeks to achieve are:  </heading>
        <paragraph>
          <num>•</num>
          <content>
            <p>Address the disproportionate growth of foundation years in classroom-based subjects – Targeting the lower fee limit at foundation years in classroom-based subjects will reduce the financial incentives for HE providers to continue growing this provision.  </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>•</num>
          <content>
            <p>Improve the value for money for classroom-based foundation years – The reduced fee level represents a fairer deal for students and will reduce the taxpayer subsidy in foundation years that may not be valuable or necessary. The new lower fee level is also aligned with funding rates for AHE Diplomas, so that student pay a fair price for provision that is functionally similar.  </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>•</num>
          <content>
            <p>Protect funding for foundation years in higher cost and strategically valuable subjects – Fees for subjects like STEM and medicine will remain aligned with the maximum fee limits for the relevant academic year, ensuring that foundation years in these subjects remain financially viable for providers to deliver so that students from underrepresented backgrounds can continue to use them as an access route to courses in these subjects.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Provider-Level Impact</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>The impact assessment published alongside the HE consultation response in July 2023 set out the case for change and the expected costs and benefits to providers, students and taxpayers.<authorialNote marker="28"><p> <a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/64b1427707d4b8000d3472dc/Higher_education_policy_statement_and_reform_-_government_consultation_response_-_impact_assessments_and_analysis.pdf"><u>https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/64b1427707d4b8000d3472dc/Higher_education_policy_statement_and_reform_-_government_consultation_response_-_impact_assessments_and_analysis.pdf</u></a>   </p></authorialNote> This impact assessment updates its analysis with the latest data and evidence.</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Under the preferred option, the lowering of tuition fees and loan limits would apply to all OfS registered providers in the Approved (Fee Cap) and Approved categories of the OfS register. As of 1st November 2024, there are 422 HE providers registered with the OfS, of which 343 are in the Approved (fee cap) category.</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Figure 3: Structure of HE sector in England as of academic year 2022/23: number of providers (student FTE in brackets)</b><authorialNote marker="29"><p> FECs identified through the College accounts academic year 2022 to 2023 data. The student numbers (FTE) available from the OfS was last updated on 16 October 2024. Figures presented have been rounded to the nearest thousand except for Approved FECs which are rounded to the nearest 10. There was only student number data for 410 providers. Additionally, 10 providers had zero number of students in the data.</p></authorialNote></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p />
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><i>Internal analysis of OfS data —  </i><a href="https://www.officeforstudents.org.uk/for-providers/regulatory-resources/guide-to-the-ofs-register/"><i><u>https://www.officeforstudents.org.uk/for-providers/regulatory-resources/guide-to-the-ofs-register/</u></i></a></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>There was a total of 106 Approved (fee cap) providers in England offering foundation years in academic year 2022/23, of which 82 providers had foundation year entrants for classroom-based subjects. The remaining 24 providers are assumed not to be impacted by the policy given they do not offer foundation years in classroom-based subjects.</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b><i>Methodological approach and modelling assumptions</i></b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <heading>The expected impacts on HE providers, students and the taxpayer of lowering the maximum tuition fee for classroom-based foundation years will depend on the number of UK domiciled students studying this provision in academic year 2025/26. Accordingly, by way of sensitivity analysis, we have considered the impact under two highly illustrative scenarios based on different modelling assumptions about forecast foundation year student growth in Price Group D subjects: </heading>
        <paragraph>
          <num>•</num>
          <content>
            <p><b><i>Scenario 1 (no student growth)</i></b>: student entrant numbers for foundation years (including classroom-based subjects designated as Price Group D) in academic year 2025/26 onwards are the same as in academic year 2022/23. This scenario provides a lower bound estimate of the potential lowering in the value of UK tuition fee income in academic year 2025/26.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>•</num>
          <content>
            <p><b><i>Scenario 2 (high growth)</i></b>: student entrant numbers for foundation years (including classroom-based subjects designated as Price Group D) continue rising at the same as the average growth for the last 3 years of data (academic years 2020/21-2022/23 inclusive), which is assumed to vary across provider typology, until academic year 2025/26 when student numbers remain as the same level following the fee and loan limit reduction for future years within the appraisal period. This scenario provides a high bound estimate of the potential lowering in the value of UK tuition fee income in academic year 2025/26.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </level>
