      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>The potential savings to the taxpayer are estimated using the DfE’s student loan earnings and repayment model.<authorialNote marker="30"><p> <a href="https://explore-education-statistics.service.gov.uk/methodology/student-loan-forecasts-for-england"><u>https://explore-education-statistics.service.gov.uk/methodology/student-loan-forecasts-for-england</u></a> </p></authorialNote> This is a sophisticated financial model that generates projections of future earnings for student loan borrowers which are then used to estimate the repayments that the department can expect to receive on its expenditure on student loans. The savings to the taxpayer are expressed in terms of savings in total upfront government outlay and savings in the amount of loan outlay written off by the department at the end of the repayment period (known as the RAB charge).</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>It should be noted that estimates of the expected reduction in provider income associated with a fall in tuition fees for classroom-based foundation years are based on different student number growth projection assumptions to those used to estimate the potential financial impact of raising tuition fees for all undergraduate courses which are set out in a separate impact assessment. As such, the two sets of financial impacts estimates are not directly comparable and should not be aggregated to estimate the combined financial impact of both policies on HE providers. Furthermore, total income of impacted providers has not been forecasted, with estimated changes in total income for academic year 2025/26 calculated from actual total income for the academic year 2022/23. </p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>As Figure 1 above showed, low and unknown tariff providers are the primary providers of classroom-based foundation years – accounting for 81% of the 40,745 students on OfS Price Group D foundation years in academic year 2022/23 – and are thus likely to be most impacted. This is reflected within the financial impact analysis, which shows over 80% of the £154-239m average annual income loss from lowering tuition fee income is expected to occur at low and unknown tariff providers.</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <heading>Table 4 below sets out the expected financial impacts by provider typology. To note, Table 4 and other income figures referenced throughout this impact assessment should be examined with caution. This is because:</heading>
        <paragraph>
          <num>•</num>
          <content>
            <p>Income loss estimations rely upon one academic year – academic year 2022/23 is the latest year of finance data from HESA. We have not forecasted annual income beyond academic year 2022/23.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>•</num>
          <content>
            <p>Income loss estimations exclude four providers (78 vs 82) with entrants for classroom-based foundation years due to incomplete finance data. A review of the non-financial characteristics of excluded providers does not suggest a distortion of the remaining provider data as a result.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>•</num>
          <content>
            <p>The percentage decrease in total income under Scenario 2 (maximum) of the preferred option is overstated. This is because Scenario 2 forecasts high student growth up to and including academic year 2025/26, but as total income has not been forecasted, does not account for increases in tuition fee revenue from student growth.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>•</num>
          <content>
            <p>The financial impact of the reform is dependent upon the behavioural responses of providers and students alike. It is unclear what mitigating actions providers may take to smooth annual income over the ten-year appraisal period.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
