      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Small-sized providers will not be exempt from the lower tuition fee limit to ensure all HE providers are treated equally under this policy. We want classroom-based foundation years to represent better value for money for students and taxpayers, regardless of where they are studied. DfE’s analysis does not suggest this policy will have a disproportionate financial impact on small-sized HE providers. As Table 5 shows, only one small-sized provider offered classroom-based foundation years in academic year 2022/23, with the financial effect of the reform estimated to be lower than the average annual income loss of all impacted providers.</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>The impact on medium-sized providers appears to be significantly higher than both the estimated impact on small-sized providers and overall average. Whilst comparisons to small-sized providers should be avoided due to the very small sample size; the more significant impact on medium-sized providers is primarily due to two providers with exceptionally high estimated annual income loss (9.94% to 20.66%). Excluding these two providers aligns the average for medium-sized (1.90% to 2.43%) and all classroom-based foundation year providers.</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Overall, our analysis does not indicate a disproportionate financial impact on providers due to provider size or tariff grouping. Rather, changes in income post-reform will be driven by the prominence of foundation years within undergraduate courses, and the split between classroom and non-classroom-based foundation years. In the case of the two medium-sized providers with exceptionally high estimated annual income losses, classroom-based subjects accounted for 97-100% of foundation year enrolments in academic year 2022/23. </p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num><b>7.</b></num>
        <content>
          <p><b>Regulatory scorecard for preferred option</b></p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Summary of preferred policy option</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>The option is to lower the maximum tuition fee and loan limit to £5,760 for foundation years in classroom-based subjects from academic year 2025/26. The figure of £5,760 is equivalent to the level of funding for an AHE Diploma of 600 credits in the highest standard band, using the new skills funding rates which will apply from academic year 2024/25<authorialNote marker="33"><p> The hourly funding rate for a high skilled band course under the new funding arrangements is £9.60, details found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/further-education-adult-skills-funding-rates-and-funding-for-innovative-provision/further-education-adult-skills-funding-rates-and-funding-for-innovative-provision"><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/further-education-adult-skills-funding-rates-and-funding-for-innovative-provision/further-education-adult-skills-funding-rates-and-funding-for-innovative-provision</u></a>   </p></authorialNote>. Maximum fee and loan limits for foundation years in all other subjects will remain aligned with the maximum limits for standard undergraduate courses (£9,535 for academic year 2025/26).</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>This represents a fair compromise between maintaining the viability of higher cost foundation years provision, addressing the disproportionate growth in classroom-based foundation years, and ensuring that students can access lower cost foundation years at a fairer price.</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <content>
          <p><b>Part A: Overall and stakeholder impacts </b></p>
          <table uk:widths="1.27in 3.97in 1.52in">
            <tr>
              <td colspan="2">
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>(1) Overall impacts on total welfare </b></p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Directional rating</b></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Note: Below are examples only</b></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Description of overall expected impact</b></p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text">The lowering of tuition fees paid by students on classroom-based foundation years represents an economic transfer from the HE provider to the students and in turn the taxpayer (who funds SLC tuition fees loans up-front and subsidises them to the extent that they are not paid back in full). </p>
                <p class="ia-table-text">Therefore, the overall impact on total welfare is expected to be neutral. </p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Neutral</b></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b><i>Based on all impacts (incl. non-monetised)</i></b></p>
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Monetised impacts</b></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text">£0 NSPV</p>
                <p class="ia-table-text">A decrease in tuition fees for classroom-based foundation years will represent a financial cost for businesses (HE providers), and a benefit to students and the taxpayer. The benefit to students who take out student loans will be lower loan outlay, which includes both the proportion of loan repaid and unpaid (RAB charge). Students will benefit from overall lower repaid loans, and the taxpayer will benefit from lower unpaid loans.</p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Neutral</b></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b><i>Based on likely £NPSV</i></b></p>
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Non-monetised impacts</b></p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text">Unquantified Cost: Potential reduction in access and choice associated with classroom-based foundation years if lower tuition fee income results in HE providers scaling back or withdrawing foundation year provision because it is no longer financially viable.  </p>
                <p class="ia-table-text">Unquantified Benefit: Potential for better alignment of foundation year provision with the future skills needs of employers and the UK economy and improved value for money to students and taxpayers.</p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Neutral</b></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Any significant or adverse distributional impacts?</b></p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text">See sections below</p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Neutral</b></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
              </td>
            </tr>
          </table>
          <table uk:widths="1.27in 3.97in 1.52in">
            <tr>
              <td colspan="2">
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>(2) Expected impacts on businesses </b></p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Directional rating</b></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Description of overall expected impact</b></p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text">We estimate that lowering the maximum fee limits for foundation year provision in classroom-based subjects will reduce the total amount of tuition fees income that HE providers receive from these courses (between £154m and £239m on average per year)<authorialNote marker="34"><p class="ia-table-text"> Income loss reflects average annual loss over appraisal period (2025/26 to 2034/35).</p></authorialNote>, based on our highly illustrative scenarios and modelling assumptions. Medium, low and unknown tariff providers are expected to be particularly affected since they account for over 90% of the total estimated income lost, over the appraisal period.  The annual income lost has been estimated to account for 5% of total income or more, for 8 (min) to 11 (max) providers.</p>
                <p class="ia-table-text">These are estimates of the <u>unmitigated</u> financial impact of the policy. Providers may be able to offset these potential income losses by recruiting larger numbers of students onto other courses (capacity constraints allowing). Alternatively, providers may scale back or cease provision of classroom-based foundation years where there is no longer a financial incentive to offer them (due to the lower fee limit); their reduced spending on such foundation years would mitigate the loss of fee income. </p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Negative</b></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Monetised impacts</b></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text">Based on the above annual cost figures, the business NPV is estimated to be between -£1,309m and -£2,035m (2025 prices and 2025 present value) over the 10-year period starting in 2025/26. </p>
                <p class="ia-table-text">The Equivalent Annual Net Direct Cost to Business (EANDCB) is estimated to range between £152m and £236m, without any admin costs (which are assumed to be negligible). </p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Negative</b></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Non-monetised impacts</b></p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text">​​We expect possible changes in the portfolio of foundation year provision offered by HE providers. This could include a potential contraction in supply of foundation years, based on emerging HESA data for the most recent academic year. It shows that the annual rate of growth of entrants has slowed to its lowest level since academic year 2012/12 – 4%. Low and unknown tariff providers, which accounted for 70% of all foundation year entrants in 2022/23, saw -2% growth in entrants for 2022/23. </p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Neutral</b></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Any significant or adverse distributional impacts?</b></p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text">The financial impact will fall mainly on Low and unknown tariff providers as they account for the majority of classroom-based foundation years provision. However, the impact will be relatively small compared to their total income (1.6 to 2.6%).</p>
                <p class="ia-table-text">The financial impact will be proportionately greatest for specialist (creative) and Large L4/5 providers (6.5% and 5.9% of their income respectively in Scenario 2 – see Table 4 above).</p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Negative</b></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
              </td>
            </tr>
          </table>
          <table uk:widths="1.27in 3.97in 1.52in">
            <tr>
              <td colspan="3">
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>(3) Expected impacts on students </b></p>
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Description of overall business impact</b></p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text">Students who enrol on foundation years in classroom-based subjects will benefit from the lower fees. As well as improving the value for money they receive from this provision, lower fees will also reduce the total amount of student debt they incur should they progress to a first degree. Lower fees may induce some students who are comparatively more cost sensitive and debt averse<authorialNote marker="35"><p class="ia-table-text"> <a href="https://www.llakes.ac.uk/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/RP-58.-Callender-and-Mason.pdf"><u>https://www.llakes.ac.uk/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/RP-58.-Callender-and-Mason.pdf</u></a> </p></authorialNote> to now pursue HE because they perceive the cost of study to have fallen. This effect may be offset by a reduction in the number of places available on foundation years in classroom-based subjects if providers respond to the reduced profit incentive by reducing provision. </p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Positive</b></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Monetised impacts</b></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text">The financial impact on students is difficult to predict due to uncertainty around future foundation year student numbers. If foundation year student numbers remain the same as they were in 2022/23, the savings for students are estimated to be around £154m on average per year, in loan outlay. Assuming foundation year student numbers grow in line with average growth from 2020/21 to 2022/23 (14% per annum), the savings for students are estimated to be £239m<authorialNote marker="36"><p class="ia-table-text"> Assumes continued growth of 14% for initial year of reform only (2025/26). </p></authorialNote> in loan outlay on average and per year.​</p>
                <p class="ia-table-text">However, because not all students fully repay their loans, the overall net savings to students should equate to the savings in the overall repaid loans for students, and the remaining will be covered by the Exchequer (see next section).</p>
                <p class="ia-table-text">​Based on the above figures, the students’ NPV is estimated to be between £930m and £1,445m (2025 prices and 2025 present value) over the 10-year period starting in 2025. The Equivalent Annual Net Direct Cost to Households (EANDCH) is estimated to range between -£108m and -£168m, without any admin costs. However, these savings are a transfer from providers to students. They represent a benefit to students equivalent to the proportion of tuition fees repaid on average, and the remaining will be a saving to the Exchequer in terms of RAB charge<authorialNote marker="37"><p class="ia-table-text"> See RAB charge forecasts here: <a href="https://explore-education-statistics.service.gov.uk/find-statistics/student-loan-forecasts-for-england/2023-24"><u>https://explore-education-statistics.service.gov.uk/find-statistics/student-loan-forecasts-for-england/2023-24</u></a>  </p></authorialNote>. </p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Positive</b></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Non-monetised impacts</b></p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text">There may be positive and negative non-monetised impacts which may offset one another in the aggregate (hence neutral rating overall).</p>
                <p class="ia-table-text">We anticipate the reform will lead to providers contracting provision of classroom-based foundation years. This may reduce access and choice for students. Additionally, there may be a risk HE providers reduce the quality of provision for classroom-based foundation years in order to lower costs in line with the reduced fee limit. </p>
                <p class="ia-table-text">On the other hand, the potential constraints in access and choice may result in potential entrants utilising alternative pathways into HE, such as AHE courses, which serve a similar purpose. Additionally, impacted courses do not tend to have specific entry requirements, therefore providers may choose to provide immediate entry into year 1 instead of the foundation year for more students, which would improve the value for money for students and the Exchequer.  </p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Neutral</b></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Any significant or adverse distributional impacts?</b></p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text">​​The reform would be likely to improve value for money by reducing the fee and loan limits for classroom-based subjects, helping to ensure students are charged a fairer price for lower-cost provision that may not require an additional year of study. </p>
                <p class="ia-table-text">Whilst we do not expect a significant change in foundation year courses offered, sufficient alternative routes into HE remains (e.g. HTQs, other L4/5 courses, AHEs, etc.). We believe these alternatives offer sufficient options for students who may be displaced by the reduction or withdrawal of some foundation year provision. Many of these options are also available at lower cost to students than foundation years.</p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Neutral</b></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
              </td>
            </tr>
          </table>
          <table uk:widths="1.27in 3.97in 1.52in">
            <tr>
              <td colspan="3">
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>(3) Expected impacts on taxpayers</b></p>
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Description of overall household impact</b></p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text">​​Lowering tuition fees and fee loan limits for classroom-based foundation years will reduce the total amount of student loan outlay compared to the do-nothing option. It may also lead to a small reduction in the proportion of loan support to these foundation year students that is written off, represented by the Resource Accounting and Budgeting (RAB) charge<authorialNote marker="38"><p class="ia-table-text"> The RAB charge is the estimated cost to government of providing a subsidy for the student finance system. It is the amount of loan outlay issued each year which is <b>not</b> expected to be repaid, when future repayments are valued in present terms using the HMT discount rate.</p></authorialNote>.​ </p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Positive</b></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Monetised impacts</b></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text">Based on the DfE’s student finance repayment model, it is estimated that, for the appraisal period covering AY 2025/26 to 2034/35, the Department for Education would save £1,403m in student outlay and £666m in subsidy costs (RDEL RAB charge). The RAB savings would occur over 40 years, as students starting courses within the appraisal period repay their loans.  </p>
                <p class="ia-table-text">The student finance model assumes low growth in the number of foundation year students, in line with the general growth in undergraduate numbers of around 2% per year. Therefore, the savings to the Exchequer shown below should be treated as a lower bound estimate. </p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Positive</b></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Non-monetised impacts</b></p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text">​​We do not expect the change in foundation year fee and loan limits to have significant non-monetised impacts to the taxpayer.​ </p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Neutral</b></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
              </td>
            </tr>
          </table>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <content>
          <p><b>Part B: Impacts on wider government priorities</b></p>
          <table uk:widths="1.77in 3.64in 1.21in">
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Category</b></p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Description of impact</b></p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Directional rating</b></p>
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Business environment:</b></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Does the measure </b><b>impact on the ease of doing business in the UK?</b></p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text">As the change in tuition fee limits for classroom-based foundation years does not affect the way in which a HE provider carries out its teaching, research and related activities, we do not believe this measure will limit the ability of providers, or their incentives, to compete. Since the proposed changes to maximum tuition fees apply to all Approved (fee cap) HE providers (which account for most students) we do not believe that the proposed change will affect students’ ability to engage with the sector and make choices that align with their preferences.</p>
                <p class="ia-table-text">It is possible the lower tuition fee for classroom-based subjects could strengthen providers’ incentives to introduce new technologies, products or business models which lower the cost of teaching and improve the efficiency of their activities. However, the ability of providers to exploit potential opportunities may depend on the extent to which it has sufficient financial resources available to fund the necessary investment.</p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Uncertain</b></p>
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>International Considerations:</b></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Does the measure support international trade and investment?</b></p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text">While lowering tuition fee limits for classroom-based foundation year provision only directly affects UK domiciled students, there could be an indirect positive impact on trade and investment if providers switch to recruiting more international students as a way of offsetting the lower tuition fee income they receive from domestic foundation year students. This is because expenditure by international students on tuition fees is treated as an export in the national accounts as it represents spending in the country by a non-UK resident</p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Neutral</b></p>
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Natural capital and Decarbonisation:</b></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Does the measure support commitments to improve the environment and decarbonise?</b></p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text">We do not believe that lowering tuition fees for classroom-based foundation years will have a significant negative impact on the use or management of land in the UK, the atmosphere, any type of inland, coastal or marine water body, wildlife, or opportunities for outdoor recreation. </p>
                <p class="ia-table-text">It is possible that lower levels of tuition fee income from foundation year provision could result in some HE providers having to delay or pause necessary expenditure on maintaining the campus grounds (which can include natural areas and playing fields), and investment aimed at improving the energy performance and sustainability of their buildings (some of which may be energy inefficient because of their age) as well as lowering the overall level of carbon emissions and waste generated by the HE provider’s academic facilities and residences. </p>
                <p class="ia-table-text">However, we believe the potential risk and impact to be highly uncertain. This is because tuition fees from classroom-based foundation years will account for a small proportion of the total income and funding that HE providers receive. Furthermore, HE providers are independent, autonomous institutions which are responsible for managing their assets (including the capital estate) and for making their owns decisions about how to spend the income they receive from tuition fees.</p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Neutral</b></p>
              </td>
            </tr>
          </table>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num><b>8.</b></num>
        <content>
          <p><b>Monitoring and evaluation of preferred option</b></p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>In line with the Better Regulation Framework, the department will undertake a post-implementation review in 2028 at the earliest. Given the reduction in maximum fee and loan limits will not come into force until academic year 2025/26, and there is a lag in the publication of data necessary to conduct such a review, a review in 2028 will provide an assessment of at least two academic years (2025/26, 2026/27).  This will enable DfE to evaluate the initial impact of the reform on student enrolment growth, and the availability of provision by both price group and provider.</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <heading>As part of this post-implementation review, we will examine the following questions: </heading>
        <paragraph>
          <num>•</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Has the number of classroom-based foundation years decreased?</b> DfE’s expectation is that foundation years subject to the new fee and loan limit will either be reduced or will stop expanding, relative to the pre-reform period. DfE will also assess the significance of this change (i.e. did the reform have a clear influencing role on provider behaviour?), and how the availability of provision compares to foundation years in higher cost subjects.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>•</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Has the number of students on foundation years in classroom-based subjects decreased?</b> DfE’s expectation is for a decline in the number of students studying classroom-based foundation years. We will also assess how changes in student enrolments compare to higher cost foundation years, and classroom-based degrees without a foundation year (i.e. direct entry enrolment). Furthermore, assuming a decline in student enrolment, we will endeavour to identify what pathway students, who would have undertaken a classroom-based foundation year in the absence of this reform, transition onto (e.g. direct entry into year 1, AHE diplomas, etc.).</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>•</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Has the reform indirectly affected the availability of foundation years in higher cost and strategically important subjects, and/or the number of students on them?</b> DfE does not anticipate a decrease in availability for foundation years not subject to the reduction in fee and loan limits for classroom-based subjects. However, we recognise the significant reduction in fees for classroom-based foundation years, coupled with the small increase to the maximum fee and loan limit for all other courses, may elicit a behavioural response from potential entrants and providers of higher cost courses. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>•</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Has the number of students sharing protected and other student characteristics disproportionately declined?</b> Whilst DfE expects a decline in student enrolment, we do not anticipate a disproportionate impact on students from underrepresented groups, particularly in their ability to access HE. Regardless, we will monitor if changes to students across protected characteristics are aligned with the expectations outlined within the equalities impact assessment which is being published separately.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num><b>•</b></num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Has the reform impacted student outcomes for foundation year provision?</b><b> </b>A primary objective of this policy is to realign the expansion of enrolment and provision of classroom-based foundation years with similar courses at the direct entry level (year 1). Whilst this may likely result in a decline in student enrolment and courses, we do not anticipate a decline in student outcomes, given sufficient alternative pathways and the expectation of increased direct entry offers. Nonetheless, we will monitor student progression and completion rates (published annually by the OfS), as well as student outcomes at the individual provider level. Due to the lag between entry, course completion and data publication of at least four years for full-time students, we will only be able to look at progression (onto year 1) at the time of our post-implementation review.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>•</num>
          <intro>
            <p><b>What analysis and evaluation methods will we use to answer the questions above</b><b>?</b>  We will carry over the methodology used to assess the policy outlined within this IA. </p>
          </intro>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>◦</num>
            <intro>
